## Idea:
1. Any element less than `0` or greater than `n` is useless, so change those to `0`
2. Track whether an element is present by making the element at the index negative

## Steps:
1. Assign `0` to useless terms (`nums[i] < 0 || nums[i] > n`)
    - `[3,4,-1,1] -> [3,4,0,1]`
2. Treat each element as a pointer by making the element at that index negative (taking the absolute value to ignore whether we marked it as present). The one edge case is if the element is `0`: we point to itself since we assigned `0` to the useless elements.
	1. `nums[0] = 3: [3,4,0,1] -> [3,4,-3,1]` (the third element is 0 so we point to itself)
	2. `nums[1] = 4: [3,4,-3,1] -> [3,4,-3,-1]` (we negate the fourth element)
	3. `nums[2] = -3` (no change since the third element is already negative)
	4. `nums[3] = -1: [3,4,-3,-1] -> [-3,4,-3,-1]` (we negate the first element)
3. Return the correct index for the first element that is `>= 0`

## Full solution:
```
public int firstMissingPositive(int[] nums) {
    int n = nums.length;
    for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
        if (nums[i] < 0 || nums[i] > n) {
            nums[i] = 0;
        }
    }

    for (int num : nums) {
        if (num != 0) {
            int index = Math.abs(num) - 1;
            if (nums[index] == 0) {
                nums[index] = -(index + 1);
            } else {
                nums[index] = -Math.abs(nums[index]);
            }
        }
    }

    for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
        if (nums[i] >= 0) {
            return i + 1;
        }
    }
    return n + 1;
}
```

