solutions.content:
**Floyd’s Cycle-Finding Algorithm**

Traverse linked list using one **slow** and one **fast** pointer. Move the **slow pointer** by one and the **fast pointer** by two.

**CASE 1**
If these pointers meet at the same node then there is a loop.

**CASE 2**
If pointers do not meet then the linked list doesn’t have a loop.

**EXAMPLE**
Consider the below image.
**Initially considering fast pointer = slow pointer +1 , so Distance =1.**

![Floyd-Algo-Proof](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/8be7aed7-e0d6-43c7-ae61-de4c1d359ede_1612365738.3477886.png)

**Finally, if the Distance at any point becomes zero, that is Slow==Fast then cycle found.**


**NOTE**
It is absolutely all right to start the **slow** and **fast** pointers from the first and second node respectively **or** both from the first node. ( if they exists ).


**CODE**

```
class Solution {
public:
    bool hasCycle(ListNode *head) {

        ListNode *slow=head;
        ListNode *fast;

        if(slow)
            fast=head->next; // "fast" can also start from the same node as "slow"
        else
            return false;

        while(slow||fast){  // while traversing if both of them becomes NULL together, no cycle found

            if(slow==fast) // then we got the same node again, hence cycle found
                return true; // [ CASE 1 ]

            if(slow)
                slow=slow->next; // move 1 step at a time

            if(fast){
                if(fast->next)
                    fast=fast->next->next; // move 2 step at a time
                else
                    break; // if 2 step jump not possible at any node then break from loop, hence no cycle
            }
        }
        // [ CASE 2 ]
        return false; // no cycle found at this point
    }
};
```


Considering *N* to be the total number of nodes of the link list

**TIME COMPLEXITY:** O(N)
*[ Atmax the whole link list will be traversed by the slow pointer one time ]*

**SPACE COMPLEXITY:** O(1)
*[ Since no extra space is used ]*

