solutions.content:
For any operator in the string, if its left part has `m` results while the right has `n` results, we have `m * n` ways to add parenthesis. That's the basic idea. 
```java
class Solution {
    public List<Integer> diffWaysToCompute(String input) {
        List<Integer> res = new LinkedList<>();

        // find the first operator
		int k = 0;
        while (k < input.length() && Character.isDigit(input.charAt(k))) k++;

        // no operator
		if (k == input.length()) {
            res.add(Integer.parseInt(input));
            return res;
        }

		// start from the current position (the first operator)
        for (int i = k; i < input.length(); i++) {
            int c = input.charAt(i);
            if (!Character.isDigit(c)) {
			    // recursively call the fucntion to find different ways for both left and right sides of current operator
                List<Integer> left = diffWaysToCompute(input.substring(0, i));
                List<Integer> right = diffWaysToCompute(input.substring(i+1));
                for (int m: left) {
                    for (int n: right) {
                        if (c == '+') res.add(m + n);
                        else if (c == '-') res.add(m - n);
                        else res.add(m * n);
                    }
                }
            }
        }

        return res;
    }
}
