solutions.content:
My solution is intuitive ---- just divide the original string according to the operators in the string. For example, the input string is `"2*3-4*5"`, we can divide it into three different subproblems (because there are exactly three operators), as shown below :
> subproblem_1 :  ("2")  *  ("3-4 * 5")
> subproblem_2:    ("2*3") - ("4 * 5")
> subproblem_3:   ("2*3-4") * ("5")
> 
Then we can conquer these subproblems recursively. To do this, we need another two methods :
* `boolean hasNextOperator (String s, int start, int end)`
this method determines whether there exists an operator (+ , -, * ) from  the indice `start` to the `end` in the string `s`. 
* `int findNextOperator(String input, int start, int end)`
this method returns the index of the next operator, which is used to divide the current problem and to calculate the expression.

Besides, we need the method `calculate(..)` to obtain the value of the expression. 
Note that, the **base case** is that the current string is just representing an integer, and we can get this integer and return it. 

Here are the code, hope it helps.

```
class Solution {
    public List<Integer> diffWaysToCompute(String input) {
        int n = input.length();
        return recur(input, 0, n-1);
    }

    public List<Integer> recur(String input, int low, int high) {
        List<Integer> result = new ArrayList<>();
        // base case : one integer
        if (!hasNextOperator(input, low, high)) {
            int num = 0;
            for (int i = low; i <= high; i++) 
                num = num * 10 + (input.charAt(i) - '0');
            result.add(num);
            return result;
        }

        int start = low;
        do {
            List<Integer> list = new ArrayList<>();
            int index = findNextOperator(input, start, high);
            // divide and conquer the subproblem
            List<Integer> left = new ArrayList<>();
            List<Integer> right = new ArrayList<>();
            left = recur (input, low, index-1);
            right = recur (input, index + 1, high);

            // combine the solutions to the subproblem
            for (int i = 0; i < left.size(); i++) {
                for (int j = 0; j < right.size(); j++) {
                    int cur = calculate (left.get(i), right.get(j), input.charAt(index));
                    list.add(cur);
                }
            }

            result.addAll(list);
            start = index + 1;
        } while (start <= high && hasNextOperator(input, start, high));

        return result;
    }

    public int findNextOperator(String input, int start, int end) {
        int index = -1;
        for (int i = start; i <= end; i++) {
            if (!Character.isDigit(input.charAt(i))) {
                index = i;
                break;
            }
        }
        return index;
