solutions.content:
The key idea is to store NestedInteger objects in stack (where `next()` is either equal to stack top or nested in it).

0. `pushList(v)` pushes elements of vector v to stack in reversed order.
1. **Initialization**. Prepare stack just pushing all NestedList elements to stack in reversed order (so that the first element is on top of stack).
2. `hasNext()` prepares next element. If the element on the stack top is integer, then it is the required next int. Otherwise, it is a nested list (vector of NestedInteger), so we pop it, push to stack its elements (via `pushList`) and repeat processing the stack top.
3. `next()` firstly prepares next using `hasNext()` and then returns it (popping it beforehand)

```
class NestedIterator {
    stack<NestedInteger> s;
public:
    NestedIterator(vector<NestedInteger> &nestedList) {
        pushList(nestedList);
    }

    int next() {
        hasNext();
        int res = s.top().getInteger();
        s.pop();
        return res;
    }

    bool hasNext() {
        while (!s.empty()) {
            if (s.top().isInteger()) {
                return true;
            }
            auto t = s.top();
            s.pop();
            pushList(t.getList());
        }
        return false;
    }

    void pushList(const vector<NestedInteger>& v) {
        for (int i = v.size() - 1; i >= 0; --i) {
            s.push(v[i]);
        }
    }
};
```

